genic mice. (<bold>A</bold>) Schematic illustration of the &#x02212;566/+35EGFP construct used to generate transgenic mice. The reporter construct contains the region 566 bp upstream and 35 bp downstream of the transcription initiation site (bent arrow at +1) of the <italic>Oxct2b</italic> gene, the coding sequence of the <italic>EGFP</italic> gene and the SV40 poly(A) signals. (<bold>B</bold>) Fluorescence and (<bold>C</bold>) bright-field images of the abdominal cavity of an adult &#x02212;566/+35EGFP transgenic mouse. EGFP fluorescence is visible only in the testes. (<bold>D</bold>) EGFP fluorescence in sections of transgenic testes. The small roman numerals indicate the stages of the seminiferous tubules.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f1"/></fig><fig id="fig2" position="float"><label>Figure 2</label><caption><p>Sequence alignment of the upstream regions of the <italic>Oxct2b</italic> (GenBank accession no. <ext-link ext-link-type="gen" xlink:href="AB105455">AB105455</ext-link>) and <italic>Oxct2a</italic> (GenBank accession no. <ext-link ext-link-type="gen" xlink:href="AB105454">AB105454</ext-link>) genes. Identical nucleotides are represented by asterisks; deletions are indicated by dashes. The numbers to the right of each sequence are relative to the transcription start site (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b23">23</xref>), which is designated as +1. The major putative consensus transcription factor binding sites, as predicted from database analysis using the internet-based TFSEARCH (<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://150.82.196.184/research/db/TFSEARCH.html"/>) are boxed (set at a cut-off score of 85). The translational initiation codon ATG at position +60 is highlighted in gray.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f2"/></fig><fig id="fig3" position="float"><label>Figure 3</label><caption><p>Deletion analysis of Oxct2b promoter activity using <italic>in vivo</italic> transient transfection of testicular germ cells. The Oxct2b promoter was deleted sequentially either upstream (<bold>A</bold>) or downstream (<bold>B</bold>) of the transcription start site, and individual deletions were fused to the <italic>luciferase</italic> reporter gene. The deletion constructs were transfected into the seminiferous tubules of mouse testes. Luciferase activity, which was normalized to that of <italic>Renilla</italic> luciferase driven by the OAZt promoter (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b25">25</xref>), is presented as the mean values (&#x000b1;SEM) of three independent experiments that were performed in duplicate. *<italic>P</italic> &#x0003c; 0.05, **<italic>P</italic> &#x0003c; 0.01 compared with &#x02212;566/+35Luc (A) and &#x02212;389/+35Luc (B) (ANOVA followed by Bonferroni analysis). The luciferase activities of &#x02013;566/+35Luc (A) and &#x02013;389/+35Luc (B) were set at 1.0.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f3"/></fig><fig id="fig4" position="float"><label>Figure 4</label><caption><p>The &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 region of the Oxct2b promoter functions as a core promoter. (<bold>A</bold>) An internal deletion that extends from &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 in the &#x02212;566/+35Luc construct abolishes Oxct2b promoter activity. <italic>In vivo</italic> transient transfection of testicular germ cells was performed with &#x00394;&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc and &#x02212;566/&#x02212;50Luc. (<bold>B</bold>) Inversion of the &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 region abolishes the transcriptional activity of the Oxct2b promoter. The constructs &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc and &#x02212;389/&#x02212;16/&#x02212;49Luc, which carry the correct orientation and inverted orientation of the indicated region, respectively, were transiently transfected into testicular germ cells. **<italic>P</italic> &#x0003c; 0.01 compared with &#x02212;389/&#x02212;50Luc (ANOVA followed by Bonferroni analysis). (<bold>C</bold>) The &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 region acts as a core element but not as an activator element. The &#x02212;49 to &#x02212;16 fragment that contains Oxct2b-CL was ligated to the 5&#x02032; end of &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc to re-position the core promoter element, and the reporter gene assays were carried out via <italic>in vivo</italic> transient transfection of testicular germ cells. Data are presented as described in the legend to <xref ref-type="fig" rid="fig3">Figure 3</xref>. The luciferase activities of &#x02013;566/&#x02212;50Luc (A), &#x02013;389/&#x02212;50Luc (B) and &#x02013;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc (C) were set at 1.0. (<bold>D</bold>) Alignment of the &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 sequence of the mouse <italic>Oxct2b</italic> gene with those of the mouse <italic>Oxct2a</italic> and human <italic>OXCT2</italic> (<italic>hOxct2</italic>) genes. Identical nucleotides are represented by asterisks; deletions are indicated by dashes. The numbers are relative to the transcription start site at +1. The Oxct2b-CL consensus is shown in boldface. The highly conserved region among these genes is boxed.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f4"/></fig><fig id="fig5" position="float"><label>Figure 5</label><caption><p>Confirmation of the haploid spermatid-specific activity of the Oxct2b promoter in transgenic mice. (<bold>A</bold>) Schematic illustration of the &#x02212;103/&#x02212;16EGFP construct used to generate transgenic mice. (<bold>B</bold>) Fluorescence image of the testis from a transgenic mouse together with the corresponding bright-field image (<bold>C</bold>). (<bold>D</bold>) Expression of EGFP fluorescence in testicular sections. The cells in the innermost layers expressed EGFP.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f5"/></fig><fig id="fig6" position="float"><label>Figure 6</label><caption><p>The Oxct2b core promoter binds specifically to CREM factor through an Oxct2b-CL motif. (<bold>A</bold>) The testis nuclear extract binds to the promoter (&#x02212;50/&#x02212;10) of the <italic>Oxct2b</italic> gene. Lane 1, without nuclear extract; lane 2, liver nuclear extract; lanes 3&#x02013;7, testis nuclear extract without competitor (lane 3), in the presence of a 100-fold molar excess of unlabeled oligonucleotides 1 (lane 7), 2 (lane 4), 3 (lane 5) and 4 (lane 6), which are shown to the left as competitors. The arrow shows testis-specific protein binding. (<bold>B</bold>) The Oxct2b-CL element in the Oxct2b promoter (&#x02212;50/&#x02212;10) binds a testis-specific nuclear protein. A 100-fold molar excess of the unlabeled wild-type (wt) or mutated (mut) promoter fragment was used as the competitor. (<bold>C</bold>) The CREM factor binds to the Oxct2b promoter (&#x02212;40/&#x02212;20) <italic>in vitro</italic>. EMSAs were performed with testis nuclear extracts in the presence of anti-CREM, anti-CREB or anti-AP-2&#x003b1; antibodies, using a labeled promoter fragment that spanned &#x02212;40 to &#x02212;20. (<bold>D</bold>) The CREM factor binds to the Oxct2b promoter in germ cell nuclei. Formaldehyde-cross-linked chromatin prepared from testicular germ cells was immunoprecipitated with anti-CREM (lane 2) or anti-CREB (lane 3) antibodies. Fragments shown were amplified using PCR performed with specific primers for the Oxct2b promoter. A sample of the total input DNA (lane 1) was included in the PCR analysis. (<bold>E</bold>) The 5&#x02032;-half of the Oxct2b-CL motif is responsible for binding the testis-specific protein. The nucleotide sequences of the wild-type probe (&#x02212;40/&#x02212;20), mutant competitor (m1&#x02013;m5) and testis-specific ACE&#x003c4; oligonucleotides are shown in the upper panel. The Oxct2b-CL motif and the positions of the mutations are shown in boldface and lowercase, respectively. The binding reactions were performed in the absence of unlabeled nucleotide (lane 1), and in the presence of a 1-fold (lanes 2, 5, 8, 11, 14, 16 and 18), 10-fold (lanes 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 17 and 19) or 100-fold (lanes 4, 7, 10 and 13) molar excess of competitor. The arrow indicates the testis-specific DNA&#x02013;protein complex.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f6"/></fig><fig id="fig7" position="float"><label>Figure 7</label><caption><p>Oxct2b-CL is indispensable for Oxct2b core promoter activity in testicular germ cells. Reporter gene assays with the 5&#x02032;-upstream constructs, which comprise &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16, mutated Oxct2b-CL in &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 (CLmut), and the correct (&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16CLmut) and inverted (&#x02212;16/&#x02212;49CLmut) sequences of &#x02212;49/&#x02212;16 ligated to the 5&#x02032; end of the CLmut and &#x02212;389/&#x02212;50, were carried out via <italic>in vivo</italic> transient transfection of testicular germ cells. The results are presented as described in the legend to <xref ref-type="fig" rid="fig4">Figure 4</xref>. **<italic>P</italic> &#x0003c; 0.01 compared with the &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc construct (ANOVA followed by Bonferroni analysis). The luciferase activity of &#x02212;389/&#x02212;49/&#x02212;16Luc was set at 1.0.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="gki652f7"/></fig><table-wrap id="tbl1" position="float"><label>Table 1</label><caption><p>The oligonucleotides used for PCR</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Construct</th><th align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Forward oligonucleotides</th><th align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Reverse oligonucleotides</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">&#x02212;566/+35EGFP</td><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">5&#x02032;-NNAGATCTCAGCAGGGAAGCCTGTTTCC-3&#x02032;</td><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">5&#x02032;-CTGAAGCTTAGCTCCGGGACAGAGAGAGA-3&#x02032;</td></tr><tr><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">&#x02212;103/&#x02212;16EGFP</td><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">5&#x02032;-NNAGATCTCAGGAATGGCCAAGGGTGTC-3&#x02032;</td><td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">5&#x02032;-CTGAAGCTTTCTGCGCTGCGTCACAGAG-3&#x02